    {
      "id": 8,
      "question": "What are the capital buffer requirements for Global Systemically Important Banks (G-SIBs) under Basel III?",
      "category": "regulatory_compliance",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "ground_truth": "G-SIBs are subject to an additional Higher Loss Absorbency (HLA) requirement beyond the standard Basel III capital requirements. This surcharge ranges from 1% to 3.5% of risk-weighted assets depending on the bank's systemic importance, classified into five buckets. The assessment methodology uses twelve indicators across five categories: size, interconnectedness, substitutability/financial institution infrastructure, complexity, and cross-jurisdictional activity. The HLA surcharge must be met with CET1 capital. Combined with the minimum CET1 (4.5%), the Capital Conservation Buffer (2.5%), and potentially the CCyB (0-2.5%), G-SIBs may need to hold total CET1 capital of up to 13% of RWA. The G-SIB list is updated annually by the Financial Stability Board (FSB).",
      "expected_entities": ["G-SIBs", "Basel_III", "HLA", "FSB", "CET1", "CCyB", "Capital_Conservation_Buffer"],
      "expected_concepts": ["systemic_importance", "loss_absorbency", "capital_surcharge", "bucket_classification", "too_big_to_fail"],
      "source_references": ["BCBS 255, G-SIB Assessment Methodology", "Basel III Framework, Section II.C"],
      "requires_multi_hop": false,
      "scoring_rubric": {
