      "category": "comparison",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "ground_truth": "The Standardized Approach (SA) and the Internal Ratings-Based (IRB) approach differ fundamentally in how they determine risk weights for credit exposures. Under the SA, risk weights are prescribed by regulators based on asset class and external credit ratings (e.g., 0% for AAA-rated sovereigns, 100% for unrated corporates), providing simplicity and comparability but limited risk sensitivity. Under the IRB approach, banks use their own internal models to estimate key risk parameters: Foundation IRB (F-IRB) requires banks to estimate only Probability of Default (PD), while Advanced IRB (A-IRB) also requires banks to estimate Loss Given Default (LGD), Exposure at Default (EAD), and maturity. The IRB approach is generally more risk-sensitive and can produce lower RWA for high-quality portfolios, but requires significant investment in modeling infrastructure and is subject to supervisory approval and ongoing validation. Under Basel III final reforms, the A-IRB approach is no longer available for certain low-default portfolios (large corporates, banks, financial institutions), and the output floor constrains the RWA benefit of internal models to no more than 27.5% below the SA.",
