      "category": "comparison",
      "difficulty": "simple",
      "ground_truth": "The GDPR and LGPD both require organizations to notify authorities and potentially affected individuals of data breaches, but differ in several key respects. Under GDPR Article 33, notification to the Supervisory Authority must occur within 72 hours of awareness of the breach, unless the breach is unlikely to result in a risk to individuals. Under the LGPD Article 48, notification to the ANPD must be made within a 'reasonable timeframe,' which the ANPD has indicated should be within 2 business days through Resolution CD/ANPD No. 15/2024. GDPR requires notification to data subjects under Article 34 when the breach is likely to result in 'high risk,' while LGPD requires notification when the breach may cause 'relevant risk or damage.' The GDPR specifies detailed minimum content for notifications including the nature of the breach, likely consequences, and measures taken. The LGPD requires similar content but also mandates information about the risks involved and the reasons for delay if notification is not immediate. GDPR penalties for failure to notify can reach up to EUR 10 million or 2% of global turnover, while LGPD penalties are capped at R$50 million per violation.",
