      "question": "How do the Basel III LCR and NSFR complement each other as short-term and long-term liquidity standards?",
      "category": "comparison",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "ground_truth": "The LCR and NSFR serve complementary but distinct purposes within the Basel III liquidity framework. The LCR addresses short-term liquidity resilience by requiring banks to hold sufficient HQLA to survive a 30-day acute stress scenario, focusing on immediate cash flow needs. The NSFR addresses structural liquidity mismatches over a one-year horizon by requiring that long-term assets are funded by sufficiently stable sources. The LCR uses a stock-based approach (HQLA stock versus net cash outflows), while the NSFR uses a balance-sheet-based approach (ASF versus RSF). They can produce different signals: a bank may have a strong LCR due to a large HQLA portfolio but weak NSFR due to excessive reliance on short-term wholesale funding to finance long-term illiquid assets. Conversely, a bank with stable long-term funding (strong NSFR) may have temporarily low HQLA holdings (weak LCR). Together, they prevent banks from gaming one ratio by creating vulnerabilities captured by the other. The LCR focuses on survival under stress, while the NSFR promotes sound funding structures under normal conditions.",
