      "category": "comparison",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "ground_truth": "The SA-CCR replaced the Current Exposure Method (CEM) and the Standardised Method (SM) for calculating counterparty credit risk exposure for derivatives. Under CEM, exposure was calculated as the current market value plus a simple add-on based on notional amount and asset class, which was criticized for not recognizing netting, margin agreements, or the distinction between margined and unmargined trades. SA-CCR addresses these shortcomings by calculating exposure as alpha times the sum of Replacement Cost (RC) and Potential Future Exposure (PFE), where alpha is 1.4. RC reflects the current exposure considering margin agreements, while PFE uses an aggregation formula that properly accounts for netting within defined hedging sets, with add-on factors varying by asset class (interest rate, foreign exchange, credit, equity, commodity). SA-CCR differentiates between margined and unmargined trade sets, providing lower exposure for margined transactions. The method also accounts for the maturity of transactions, applies a multiplier that reduces PFE when the portfolio is out of the money, and treats long and short positions differently within hedging sets, providing better risk sensitivity than CEM.",
