      "category": "audit",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "ground_truth": "Auditing compliance with BCBS 239 requires evaluating the bank against fourteen principles organized into four themes. For governance and infrastructure (Principles 1-2), auditors should assess whether the board and senior management have defined and overseen a strong data governance framework with clear roles, ownership, and accountability for data quality. For risk data aggregation (Principles 3-6), auditors must test the accuracy and integrity of risk data by reconciling source data to aggregated outputs, evaluate completeness of data capture across all risk types and business lines, verify timeliness of data aggregation (ability to produce critical risk data within prescribed timeframes including during stress), and assess adaptability of systems to produce ad-hoc risk reports. For risk reporting (Principles 7-11), auditors should evaluate whether reports are accurate, comprehensive, clear, useful, and distributed to appropriate decision-makers with adequate frequency. For supervisory review (Principles 12-14), auditors should assess remediation progress and interaction with regulators. Key audit procedures include data lineage walkthroughs, automated vs. manual process assessment, end-user computing risk evaluation, and testing of data dictionaries and metadata management. Findings are typically severe given that many G-SIBs have struggled with full compliance even years after the standard's effective date.",
