      "ground_truth": "The Basel III final reforms replaced all existing approaches for operational risk capital with the single Standardized Measurement Approach (SMA). The SMA calculates operational risk capital using two components: the Business Indicator Component (BIC), which is based on a bank's income statement items including interest, services, and financial components; and the Internal Loss Multiplier (ILM), which adjusts the BIC based on the bank's own loss history. The Business Indicator (BI) is calculated as the sum of the interest, leases, and dividends component, the services component, and the financial component. Banks are classified into three buckets based on BI size, with marginal coefficients of 12%, 15%, and 18%. Supervisors may set the ILM equal to 1 at the national level, effectively making only the BIC relevant.",
